commit_message:
Call _persist_state for UPDATE in 'state_set'

UPDATE flow doesn't call 'state_set', to set the state.
However, this is called in 'set_stack_and_resource_to_failed',
to set the stack status to FAILED. This includes reset during
stack UPDATE.

With https://review.openstack.org/#/c/245810/5, we removed UPDATE
from persisting the state as part of releasing the lock. This has
resulted in the state not being persisted for UPDATE when
'reset_stack_status' is called.

Change-Id: I8a80e329604fdec6498acca0a71723100d412384
Closes-Bug: #1523717

commit_message:
Use Tempest-lib's compute volumes_client

Compute volumes_client has been migrated to
tempest-lib- I10913f82dc3d0bef53edd67144cb47580d3c574d

Now Tempest-lib provides this client as stable interface so Tempest
should start using this from lib and remove its own copy.
Also remove its unit tests.

This commit makes Tempest to use compute volumes_client
from Tempest-lib.

Change-Id: I9909c96d6f7003a09f7694b1b1d7feac894b998f

commit_message:
Add Rally benchmarking hooks to Dragonflow

Once a rally job is configured in project-config, the
dragonflow.yaml file and scenarios will run in the gate
with Dragonflow as a plugin.
It is easy to extend and add new rally plugins and scenarios
in this repository to be used.

Change-Id: I3257acec07d0b62186fdcc27375f8237d1f0d2cc

commit_message:
Ensure endpoints returned is filtered correctly

This patch move some logic to manager layer, so that endpoints
filtered by endpoint_group project association will be included
in catalog when issue a project scoped token and using
`endpoint_filter.sql` as catalog's backend driver.

This make sure that call `list_endpoints_for_project` API has
the same endpoints with that in catalog returned for project
scoped token.

Change-Id: I56f4eb6fc524650677b627295dd4338d55164c39
Closes-Bug: #1516469

commit_message:
Enable py3 mock.patch of RuntimeError

RuntimeError is moved to builtins in Python3.x so adjust
the @mock.patch accordingly when running in Python3.x.

Change-Id: I5e1ce3ed40add635ce25bc1d80f88dc7ad9d2c59
Closes-Bug: #1522551

commit_message:
Pework functional tests of cluster_list and node_list

This patch revises functional test of cluster_list and node_list
to improve their robustness. They now verify specific cluster/node
id exists in returned list rather than the length of list.

Change-Id: Ice7af7e6f5d82ce054e5cc5df3ad9d047def343c

commit_message:
Add get_file support for senlinclient

SenlinClient should support get_file in spec.
Like following:

type: os.heat.stack
version: 1.0
properties:
  name: random_string_stack
  template:
    get_file: random_string_stack.yaml
  context:
    region_name: RegionOne
  environment:
    - get_file: env.yaml

Change-Id: I7076bdaa1bdb225171b18491c4e521ef6e7b94ae
Closes-Bug: #1510376

commit_message:
Shorten the event ID in log output for reability

The current event log output contains a long event ID that is rarely
helpful in distinguishing events from each other. This patch proposes
logging the "short ID" of the object.

Change-Id: Ie78b4c6f0a97d9f7330ccf2e3de3455acd8b1308

commit_message:
Improve logging in functional testings

The default logging output from functional test is too verbose to find
any useful information. This patch tries to raise the logging level so
that only useful information from the engine or the api are logged.

Change-Id: Ie68f5a752a87cf277e7fbccc01455dd121f186a5

commit_message:
[config-ref] Include neutron config files

For Mitaka, neutron implements automatic generation of sample
configuration files and removes static sample configuration
files from the neutron source tree. Therefore, the
configuration reference must include local versions of
sample configuration files similar to other projects that
implement automatic generation of sample configuration files.

Change-Id: If92d048a837ffbd9ba8664559ddabe886f448a32
Closes-Bug: #1520722

Use include for swift::storage::${type}

Require operator specify swiftinit provider
on supported components rather then pass it through.

commit_message:
Import i18n functions directly

Import i18n functions from module directly and do not use
global module variables like _ = i18n._. It makes code shorter
and cleaner. It also to detect cases when these functions are not
used in module.

Change-Id: Iaa593ac1f2dd15cbcad049bef6ba68f1cfa610da

commit_message:
Notify about port create/update unconditionally

The notification about port create/update should be done no matter
if host (or any other field) was changed or not - it should be up to
handler to decide how to handle it.

This also fixes the bug when there was actually no notification to l3
dvr agent on compute node on new port creation:
_get_host_port_if_changed() always returned None - this is a regression
from commit 2ee08c3464c53abaf9bc5493132ad7958611e3b8

Closes-Bug: #1521524
Change-Id: I5bb416d2aaab632526f06a5620c0a4ea96340d21
(cherry picked from commit 87ce73141dddb840ffc523f253fdf87aef11d1c7)

commit_message:
LIO: Handle initiator IQNs as case insensitive

If there is a mismatch in case between the stored
initiator IQN in the LIO ACL vs. the IQN provided
in a later call, rtstool would fail to find the
existing ACL.

Compare IQNs in a case insensitive manner to ensure
they will always match as intended.  (Refer to RFC
3720 section 3.2.6.1 for details on this.)

Closes-Bug: #1522053

Change-Id: I6f535f3f4fbfcbbb49da30cffb08d17b3cac778a

commit_message:
Added test coverage for toast.service.js

Test coverage added to framework/widgets/toast/toast.service.js and
modified multiple tests to handle type of 'error', which was not tested
before.

Closes-Bug: #1499142

Change-Id: Ib34a8334e984b9600e9c2de606b43a2a3486a9d0
Co-Authored-By: Peter Tang <ptang@thoughtworks.com>

commit_message:
Add Guru Meditation Reports support to Neutron services

This new feature allows services to dump valuable debug info to stderr
on SIGUSR2 signal.

Change-Id: If17b57f687558e23b830eae5ee1f8900356355e4
Implements: blueprint guru-meditation-report

commit_message:
Add libvirt-python to ceilometer hosts

Ceilometer utilizes the libvirt library for gathering
instance related metrics. This commit adds the package
to the ceilometer hosts.

Change-Id: I1e46a9a49b606e11cd12f06ce947990096b1ad08
Closes-Bug: #1522250
(cherry picked from commit edf69b4969d7c3bf98db358b7a2c7894e5c4113a)

commit_message:
Use project throughout openrc

This is less ambitious than trying to convert the entire world to use v3
authentication. For now simply replace OS_TENANT_NAME with OS_PROJECT_NAME
because all the CLIs should be able to handle that by now.

Change-Id: If473b2eb74d26afa5ff22b7ab6afca25878b923e

commit_message:
Allow saving and caching the plugin auth state

Particularly for allowing the CLI to store and reuse previous
authentication allow an application to extract and reinstall the
auth state from a plugin.

Implements: bp cachable-auth
Change-Id: I4eebe7ff8060a37f19af5decfa3a8313cfb7c207

commit_message:
Use certmonger for certs

Replace custom openssl certificate generation with calls to the
certmonger local CA. Ideally we would use the certmaster backend for
devstack however it lacks some features we require.

Change-Id: Ib0164bb27233e2b67b1580ce350a5ea9e4330834

commit_message:
Make root_stack_id determination more robust

If a stack with stack_id does not exist, then the
function should return None.

Change-Id: Ib1670be42d092629d97552b79960cdcf0ace1fb2
Closes-Bug: #1524472

commit_message:
Fix decription for admins Image create modal

Current admins image create modal
description/helpbox contains inaccurate
description.
Glance can store compressed images, but
Nova can't boot from compressed images.
This patch deletes mentioning compressed
images as supported type for admin
page.

Change-Id: I1e8972688d096692c6746f7a2f4a2dcf71ffabbf
Partial-Bug: #1479966
Co-Authored-By: Alan Fung<wingfung@cisco.com>

commit_message:
Statically handle default auth options

Don't compile all the possible auth options for everything on the system
into the --help text of OSC. Keystoneclient handles this by only
registering the options specified in --os-auth-plugin. Do something
similar for OSC and make it so that if the user doesn't provide a plugin
we handle the options manually so we don't get messed up by plugins that
do weird things.

Change-Id: I609204172deacd76bde7edbd5096aee310eeb716

commit_message:
Load auth plugins directly

There is no need for OSC to determine a plugin name and then look that
up in stevedore. If it knows the plugin it wants then it should access
it directly. This means we don't add new plugins to the global stevedore
pool because these plugins are available to everything on the system.

Centralize all the hacks for loading these plugins. It's a big function
but now there is one place where you give some options and you get back
a plugin. This will make it easier to refactor later where we have the
same pattern.

Change-Id: I44f720cf43f6a7d0a19a10760a0f63e1a48af09e

commit_message:
Use keystoneclient's session loading from CLI

The keystoneclient provides a standard mechanism for loading transport
options from a CLI. This will remove some handling from OSC as well as
give it the ability to specify client certificates.

This removes the verify parameter from the ClientManager as this is an
option that is handled by the session loading mechanism. The verify
argument that is not provided by keystoneclient is mapped to the
insecure parameter that is.

Change-Id: I7deb0489c6237465608521d8750fbca2ea24aa65

commit_message:
Add "vnc" option group for sample nova.conf file

There is no "[vnc]" section in nova.conf.sample generated by
command "tox -egenconfig".
In addition, the "[default]" section has vnc options.

This patch moves vnc options from "[default]" section to
"[vnc]" section.

Change-Id: I5cf69729aa9e2bb868f26b82eaaa28187ce7a7a3
Closes-Bug: #1506356

commit_message:
Move consistency group quota checks to API

Currently quotas are sometimes checked in cinder.volume.manager,
and other times checked in cinder.volume.api. This patch is the
second of two commits that aim to make these checks more consistent
by moving calls from the manager to the API. This way, we can give
the user feedback before launching the RPC call. If the quotas fail
to update, an exception will be raised in the API to inform the user
before the action takes place unless the force option is set to True.

APIImpact
Closes-bug: #1508249
Depends-On: I49e3e2bf3e1621e9e8d9645b7ad09154ffb448c3

In a previous comment, Lin mentioned setting OS_PROJECT_DOMAIN_NAME.  I see that isn't being done in the latest patch, but I don't think that's necessary as OS_PROJECT_ID gets set, and project ID's are unique across domains.

I tried this out in our environment that has projects under non-default domains, and it works fine just setting OS_PROJECT_ID.

Just wanted to make sure we're all on the same page on that topic, since I didn't see resolution of it in the comments.

This looks good to me the way it is."}, {'account_id': 9237, 'date': '2015-09-11 17:38:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

commit_message:
Adding download for openrc file for keystone v3

The existing openrc file download only works for keystone v2. Regardless
of whether v3 is enabled in Horizon.

This adds support for both. A v2.0 and a v3 compatible openrc file
download. A couple of different situations are covered.

1) support for keystone v2 only: OPENSTACK_API_VERSION={'identity': 2.0}
In this case only the v2 option is shown.

2) Use of keystone v3 in a potentially mixed environment. Since it is
possible to use keystone v2 and v3 in the same enviroment, having
OPENSTACK_API_VERSION={'identity': 3} displays options for downloading
v2 or v3 compatible openrc files.

Rationale for making the existing methods and urls support v3+. By
moving the v2.0 functionality to new version specific methods, they can
be more easily excised when v2 is obsolete and we're left with the newer
version support.

Change-Id: I29c62dc7436cc39adc1a4af9d90ceb6767e7a177
Closes-Bug: #1460150

commit_message:
Use assertDictEqual instead of assertEqualPolicies

The assertEqualPolicies methods was recently refactored
(I7b6ec22430fcffae69cab1b276e41390314be5cc) to only call assertDictEqual. This
change removes assertEqualPolicies in place of assertDictEqual, resulting in
clearer code.

Change-Id: I4c675bac5f6cadff018e5d7d2f689d21b3e504ce

commit_message:
Improve startup performance of nova-compute Hyper-V driver

During the nova-compute driver startup, a lot of calls are made to
get_windows_version slowing down startup.
This patch speeds up the startup by caching the windows version to
be used for later calls of get_windows_version.

Change-Id: I5b2eadc0bce79cd261a5dcaac7712c23c49dfcc2

commit_message:
Improve startup performance of nova-compute Hyper-V driver

During the nova-compute driver startup, a lot of calls are made to
get_windows_version slowing down startup.
This patch speeds up the startup by caching the windows version to
be used for later calls of get_windows_version.

Change-Id: Ie555088abe20c2c6dcb8340dd61745f710a0323e

commit_message:
Automatically generate neutron LBaaS configuration files

This adds a new tox environment, genconfig, which generates sample
neutron LBaaS configuration file using oslo-config-generator.

DocImpact: Update the docs that LBaaS no longer includes static example
configuration files. Instead, use tools/generate_config_file_samples.sh
to generate them and the files generated now end with .sample extension.

Partially-Implements: blueprint autogen-neutron-conf-file

Change-Id: I25507f3bc6e995580aa91a912c2cf4110757df15
Partial-bug: #1199963

to bp:objects-from-bay.

commit_message:
Avoid to use common.cert_manager directly

Conductor has a utility to manage bay specific certificates.
This patch changes to use it.
And also this patch fixes temporary place holder classes related
to bp:objects-from-bay.

Change-Id: I55d7fe33d7a910b9ba76bcbb4c39353fe7fac2f4
Closes-Bug: #1523843

commit_message:
Fix neutron issue w/ l2pop

This change resolves an issue where neutron is not able to bind to
a given port because l2 population is disabled and no vxlan multicast
group has been defined. To resolve this the `neutron_l2_population`
variable is being defined and set to "False" in the os_neutron defaults
and the vxlan multicast group will now contain a default value instead
of an empty string.

The change also removes the neutron_l2_population checks in the tasks
and templates because the variable is now being defined.

Change-Id: Ic2973626d88781bfc67a4275afcf9feffeb63f36
Closes-Bug: #1521793
Co-Authored-by: Ville Vuorinen <ville.vuorinen@multim.fi>
Signed-off-by: Kevin Carter <kevin.carter@rackspace.com>

commit_message:
Fix mesos monitor for handling multiple masters

Magnum is going to enable HA mode for mesos bay, in which there
could be more than one master nodes. One of the master node (leader)
is active and the rest of them is not active. Mesos monitor needs to
identify the leader and pull metrics from the leader only.

Change-Id: Ic7d6cb64964db2758163bd231dec4190302155b2
Partial-Implements: blueprint mesos-multi-master-node

commit_message:
Rename analyzer/builder functions/methods

Some of the names are 'iter_*' and others are 'iterate_*'
so this just rename the 'iter_*' to be 'iterate_*' and also
hides a couple of analyzer methods that are not used
externally (and really don't need to be exposed).

Change-Id: Ibd5180a0cf2b40d914cd668137473d1fbab445cd

[{'created': '2015-12-02 12:11:42.000000000', 'message': "Take into consideration races in XtremIOClient3

When working with FC and xtremio is using XtremIOClient3 on FC's
terminate_connection we can get VolumeBackendAPIException saying a
resource could not be found when we shouldn't.

The cause is that Client3 is open to race conditions on 2 methods,
find_lunmap and num_of_mapped_volumes, where a list of mappings is first
retrieved and then we iterate this list to retrieved additional info on
the mappings.

The race would happen if one of the mappings is removed from the backend
in the time it takes to retrieve the additional info after we have
retrieved the list.

This patch fixes this issue by ignoring any mappings that have been
removed and are now NotFound when retrieving additional information for
a mapping in those 2 methods.

This patch also fixes this kind of race problems on volume creation
since it uses find_lumap method.

Closes-Bug: #1521143
Change-Id: I40831e04093ff475395870a333211dd0cb60440f
(cherry picked from commit 89480f159231eae154119da6b46432849b9df20a)

commit_message:
Take into consideration races in XtremIOClient3

When working with FC and xtremio is using XtremIOClient3 on FC's
terminate_connection we can get VolumeBackendAPIException saying a
resource could not be found when we shouldn't.

The cause is that Client3 is open to race conditions on 2 methods,
find_lunmap and num_of_mapped_volumes, where a list of mappings is first
retrieved and then we iterate this list to retrieved additional info on
the mappings.

The race would happen if one of the mappings is removed from the backend
in the time it takes to retrieve the additional info after we have
retrieved the list.

This patch fixes this issue by ignoring any mappings that have been
removed and are now NotFound when retrieving additional information for
a mapping in those 2 methods.

This patch also fixes this kind of race problems on volume creation
since it uses find_lumap method.

Closes-Bug: #1521143
Change-Id: I40831e04093ff475395870a333211dd0cb60440f
(cherry picked from commit 89480f159231eae154119da6b46432849b9df20a)

commit_message:
Remove unfixable FIXME

There is a note in test_catalog.py saying that we should fix the
endpoint create status code from 200 OK to 201 Created.

This isn't allowed according to the API working group guidelines:
http://specs.openstack.org/openstack/api-wg/guidelines/evaluating_api_changes.html#evaluating-api-changes

Change-Id: Id52c61f119d4e9b1168ddc2d1ebc760fca1d640d

commit_message:
Use new_policy_ref consistently

Do not manually create policy refs. Use new_policy_ref instead.

I have tested few scenarios and maybe it's just a triviality. But rebalance output gives number of reassigned partitions higher than 100% (accurately number of partitions multiplied by part_power). Is it right?

http://paste.openstack.org/show/478095/"}, {'account_id': 1179, 'date': '2015-11-05 18:06:10.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)

hey Pete!  Thanks for poking at it!

Yes, that is what I expect the output to be.

we reassign part-replicas - it's a map of part_num => [replica, ...]

We used to only log the number of *keys* changed, but I fixed that count up the number of part-replicas that changed.

Later when we build the dispersion_graph we always count up the number of part-replicas that moved, but it turns out the initial balance used to be a special case that was hard coded to return 100% instead of the real number of part-replicas.

We could try to bring that back, but I sorta like it... well, idk, I guess in the current state there's not really a way to tell when we moved two part-replicas if it was one replica of two parts or two replicas of one part..."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-11-06 03:00:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified-1

Clay is correct - I made a mistake in my testing where I just set "pretend_min_part_hours_passed" once on a builder file instead of after each rebalance.

This mistake surfaced with the changes made to the "small ring" in "Test Group A" in the document. Because I wasn’t setting “pretend_min_part_hours_passed” after each round of changes, the partitions that were moved in the previous change(s) were still under a time lock. As a result, the builder tool did not have the freedom of a clear run and it couldn’t balance correctly in this situation. This issue didn’t surface with the larger rings as it was a far smaller percentage of partitions that were being moved in each round.'}, {'account_id': 4608, 'date': '2015-12-07 11:41:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Code-Review-1

ok- 

(to start with- sorry that this is so long. i would have liked to just paste results of the scripts that I ran but they would show a little more detail about our clusters than folks here would probably like :) Also- i have not even looked at the code really.) 

what i did was and a new node to one of our production rings using the ring builder on master vrs this change. First, the time it took to rebalance went from 4 minutes down to < 1 minute so thats cool. But the partitions assigned to the new node were quite different.

With the current code all the drives in the new node were added really off balance (~ -15). I tried adding a second equally sized node and after the rebalance the first node was mostly fixed (~ 4) and the new node also got ~4 balance. So i don’t know why that first node was added the way it was with the initial rebalance.

With the new code that didn’t happen though. The new node got added with a balance of < 1.  So that’s good :)

the new code also seemed to repair some other nodes during the first rebalance. The current code pulled one partition from almost all the drives in the ring and 2 or 3 partitions was moved from < .1% of the drives- with a total of ~32,000 partition changes (sum(abs(change in partitions per drive))) So that was really good at spreading the changes to have a very small impact on the existing drives.  The new code was different- 2/3 of the drives had 1 partition removed and 1/3 of the drives had 2 partitions moved with a total of 48,500 partitions moved. There were also a bunch of drives (besides the one in the new node) that received partitions- i’m pretty sure this one the new ring code repairing long out of balance nodes. 

When you broke out the partition diff per server it was quite different. with the current code the vast majority of servers seemed to lose 1 partition per drive per server. With the new code it was all over the place. Most of the servers seemed to lose right around 1 partition per drive but there were a lot of one offs with weird diffs. Also about 10% of the nodes in the cluster gained partitions- around 3-4 per drive.

With these results (more to follow) I think that the new changes are better but that there should be a warning posted on upgrading. I think that after the ring change it might be a good idea to do a rebalance with the new code without adding any additional capacity. After the initial rebalance with the new code, when I added a second new node it was a huge improvement to the current code. There weren’t any of the weird outliers and then new node was added really cleanly at a great balance. So i think doing the repairs with the new code by themselves might be worth doing. You also might want to be careful if your cluster is at capacity since this might result in some increases in your existing servers.

So then I tried something else- and this could be a problem. I wanted to see what happened to the partitions themselves. since this is just about partitions i will just paste the results:

so i have:

production ring:
object.ring.gz

in current_code/again I added another new 90 drive node with master and rebalanced

in new_code/ I added a new 90 drive node with patch and rebalanced
in new_code/again I added another new 90 drive node with patch and rebalanced

http://paste.openstack.org/show/481097/

so it looks like all the partitions that were moved were not evenly distributed though all the available partitions 

i put the scripts here:
http://paste.openstack.org/show/481095/

if i did those scripts right (and sorry they are so ugly- i just threw this together) then i think that may be a bug.  I also tried the second node addition in a separate zone and same results.'}, {'account_id': 12193, 'date': '2015-12-08 00:02:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Code-Review+1

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-11-04 11:10:28.000000000', 'message': 'Put part-replicas where they go

It's harder than it sounds.  There was really three challenges.

Challenge #1 Initial Assignment
===============================

Before starting to assign parts on this new shiny ring you've
constructed, maybe we'll pause for a moment up front and consider the
lay of the land.  This process is called the replica_plan.

The replica_plan approach is separating part assignment failures into
two modes:

 1) we considered the cluster topology and it's weights and came up with
    the wrong plan

 2) we failed to execute on the plan

I failed at both parts plenty of times before I got it this close.  I'm
sure a counter example still exists, but when we find it the new helper
methods will let us reason about where things went wrong.

Challenge #2 Fixing Placement
=============================

With a sound plan in hand, it's much easier to fail to execute on it the
less material you have to execute with - so we gather up as many parts
as we can - as long as we think we can find them a better home.

Picking the right parts for gather is a black art - when you notice a
balance is slow it's because it's spending so much time iterating over
replica2part2dev trying to decide just the right parts to gather.

The replica plan can help at least in the gross dispersion collection to
gather up the worst offenders first before considering balance.  I think
trying to avoid picking up parts that are stuck to the tier before
falling into a forced grab on anything over parts_wanted helps with
stability generally - but depending on where the parts_wanted are in
relation to the full devices it's pretty easy pick up something that'll
end up really close to where it started.

I tried to break the gather methods into smaller pieces so it looked
like I knew what I was doing.

Going with a MAXIMUM gather iteration instead of balance (which doesn't
reflect the replica_plan) doesn't seem to be costing me anything - most
of the time the exit condition is either solved or all the parts overly
aggressively locked up on min_part_hours.  So far, it mostly seemds if
the thing is going to balance this round it'll get it in the first
couple of shakes.

Challenge #3 Crazy replica2part2dev tables
==========================================

I think there's lots of ways "scars" can build up a ring which can
result in very particular replica2part2dev tables that are physically
difficult to dig out of.  It's repairing these scars that will take
multiple rebalances to resolve.

... but at this point ...

... lacking a counter example ...

I've been able to close up all the edge cases I was able to find.  It
may not be quick, but progress will be made.

Basically my strategy just required a better understanding of how
previous algorithms were able to *mostly* keep things moving by brute
forcing the whole mess with a bunch of randomness.  Then when we detect
our "elegant" careful part selection isn't making progress - we can fall
back to same old tricks.

Validation
==========

We validate against duplicate part replica assignment after rebalance
and raise an ERROR if we detect more than one replica of a part assigned
to the same device.

In order to meet that requirement we have to have as many devices as
replicas, so attempting to rebalance with too few devices w/o changing
your replica_count is also an ERROR not a warning.

Random Thoughts
===============

As usual with rings, the test diff can be hard to reason about -
hopefully I've added enough comments to assure future me that these
assertions are make sense.

Despite being a large rewrite of a lot of important code, the existing
code is know to have failed us.  This change fixes a critical bug that's
trivial to reproduce in a critical component of the system.

There's probably a bunch of error messages and exit status stuff that's
not as helpful as it could be considering the new behaviors.

Change-Id: I1bbe7be38806fc1c8b9181a722933c18a6c76e05
Closes-Bug: #1452431

commit_message:
Put part-replicas where they go

It's harder than it sounds.  There was really three challenges.

Challenge #1 Initial Assignment
===============================

Before starting to assign parts on this new shiny ring you've
constructed, maybe we'll pause for a moment up front and consider the
lay of the land.  This process is called the replica_plan.

The replica_plan approach is separating part assignment failures into
two modes:

 1) we considered the cluster topology and it's weights and came up with
    the wrong plan

 2) we failed to execute on the plan

I failed at both parts plenty of times before I got it this close.  I'm
sure a counter example still exists, but when we find it the new helper
methods will let us reason about where things went wrong.

Challenge #2 Fixing Placement
=============================

With a sound plan in hand, it's much easier to fail to execute on it the
less material you have to execute with - so we gather up as many parts
as we can - as long as we think we can find them a better home.

Picking the right parts for gather is a black art - when you notice a
balance is slow it's because it's spending so much time iterating over
replica2part2dev trying to decide just the right parts to gather.

The replica plan can help at least in the gross dispersion collection to
gather up the worst offenders first before considering balance.  I think
trying to avoid picking up parts that are stuck to the tier before
falling into a forced grab on anything over parts_wanted helps with
stability generally - but depending on where the parts_wanted are in
relation to the full devices it's pretty easy pick up something that'll
end up really close to where it started.

I tried to break the gather methods into smaller pieces so it looked
like I knew what I was doing.

Going with a MAXIMUM gather iteration instead of balance (which doesn't
reflect the replica_plan) doesn't seem to be costing me anything - most
of the time the exit condition is either solved or all the parts overly
aggressively locked up on min_part_hours.  So far, it mostly seemds if
the thing is going to balance this round it'll get it in the first
couple of shakes.

Challenge #3 Crazy replica2part2dev tables
==========================================

I think there's lots of ways "scars" can build up a ring which can
result in very particular replica2part2dev tables that are physically
difficult to dig out of.  It's repairing these scars that will take
multiple rebalances to resolve.

... but at this point ...

... lacking a counter example ...

I've been able to close up all the edge cases I was able to find.  It
may not be quick, but progress will be made.

Basically my strategy just required a better understanding of how
previous algorithms were able to *mostly* keep things moving by brute
forcing the whole mess with a bunch of randomness.  Then when we detect
our "elegant" careful part selection isn't making progress - we can fall
back to same old tricks.

Validation
==========

We validate against duplicate part replica assignment after rebalance
and raise an ERROR if we detect more than one replica of a part assigned
to the same device.

In order to meet that requirement we have to have as many devices as
replicas, so attempting to rebalance with too few devices w/o changing
your replica_count is also an ERROR not a warning.

Random Thoughts
===============

As usual with rings, the test diff can be hard to reason about -
hopefully I've added enough comments to assure future me that these
assertions make sense.

Despite being a large rewrite of a lot of important code, the existing
code is known to have failed us.  This change fixes a critical bug that's
trivial to reproduce in a critical component of the system.

There's probably a bunch of error messages and exit status stuff that's
not as helpful as it could be considering the new behaviors.

Change-Id: I1bbe7be38806fc1c8b9181a722933c18a6c76e05
Closes-Bug: #1452431

commit_message:
Scheduler: honor the glance metadata for hypervisor details

The scheduler would not honor the glance image metadata for
'hypervisor_type' and 'hypervisor_version_requires'. This was due
to the fact that this was not part if the image_meta object.

Change-Id: I03742cc9330814e2758184d8189a5be93a2b978b
Closes-bug: #1523503
(cherry picked from commit f33dfa0647f0cd289bce19f7c06b3d0a88070a92)

commit_message:
Convert headers to lower-case when parsing metadata

In urllib3 1.11.0 (and consequently, requests 2.8.0) handling was added
to preserve the casing of headers as they arrived over the wire. This
means that when iterating over a CaseInsensitiveDict from requests (as
we do in _image_meta_from_headers) we no longer get keys that are
already all lowercase. As a result, we need to ensure that the header
key is lowercased before checking its properties.

Co-Authored-By: Steve Lewis <stevelle@gmail.com>
Change-Id: I61d73763a2cc42f9af8df972095afa8e3c5e8267
Closes-bug: #1476770

Create V9 Role Driver

In preparation for new role driver methods for implied roles, this
patch creates a new version of the role driver.

Partially Implements@ blueprint implied-roles

(2 comments)

David - understand your concern - I'm scared both ways! If we say that we will only have the "latest sql model", then we either must make it backward compatible for the N-1 driver code...or change the N-1 driver code to make that still work. My problem with the later is - I don't think we are doing driver versioning so that someone can still run the standard N-1 driver. We are doing versioning so that someone can run their custom N-1 driver. How would changing our standard N-1 driver help them?'}, {'account_id': 7725, 'date': '2015-11-20 22:43:36.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 17:

(2 comments)

Henry, I'm not worried about helping custom N-1 drivers by changing our N-1 driver, I'm worried about us. If we are to keep our implementation (which I don't know that we should do) and we encourage its use (by creating V8 entrypoints in the setup.cfg) then we have to worry about which DB version we have and selectively apply migrations based on what driver is configured. IMO maybe we keep our V8 around only to test the interface, but move it into the tests directory so it can't be used by a deployment."}, {'account_id': 5707, 'date': '2015-11-21 08:42:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 17:

[{'created': '2015-11-08 15:25:25.000000000', 'message': "Created new version of assignment driver interface

In preparation for removing a series of driver methods in
the rationalization of assignment in follow-on patches, we
first create a V9 version of the driver interface. In this
patch, of course, both V8 and V9 are identical.

WORK IN PROGRESS (DO NOT MERGE)

So I think this is the first time we have actually made a new
driver version - so I was kind of shooting in the dark. Is this
what we had in mind? Currently this blows up big time since:

1) Our SQL database fixtures scans the tree and loads all the
modules at the start - and didn't allow for us having multiple
versions of modules. I tried to fix that by passing it the
versions you want to run.  This works (sort of) and you can run
tox - test_backend_sql.SQLIdentityV8 successfully. However, if you
run the whole of the SQL tests is fails since you try and reload
a second version of the module

2) Someone added some funky backend assertion code in our LDAP
test - which now fail to match the right driver.  Haven't yet
looked at how to fix that up.

Can anyone shed light on how we are meant to be doing this?

Partially Implements: blueprint blueprint assignment-manager-cleanup
Change-Id: Iefa13b64084b8e71c881ae08e1ec434d24756c17

"}, {'created': '2015-11-10 08:58:41.000000000', 'message': "Create new version of assignment driver interface

In preparation for removing a series of driver methods in
the rationalization of assignment in follow-on patches, we
first create a V9 version of the driver interface. In this
patch, of course, both V8 and V9 are identical.

WORK IN PROGRESS (DO NOT MERGE) BUT PLEASE DO REVIEW

So I think this is the first time we have actually made a new
driver version - so I was kind of shooting in the dark. Is this
what we had in mind? What I have done is:

1) Copy the sql and ldap V8 drivers into their own directory
2) Increased the version of the (new) standard driver to V9
3) Created tests that run the standard sql/ldap Identity tests
against the V8 driver to show, going forward, it is still working.
Since we assume that we never change the sqlalchemy models during
a test run, this turned out to be slight more complex than
anticipated - so created a new tox envlist target for legacy
drivers.

TO DO:

Someone added some funky backend assertion code in our LDAP
tests - which now fail to match the right driver when we use the
legacy driver.  Haven't yet looked at how to fix that up.

Partially Implements: blueprint blueprint assignment-manager-cleanup
Change-Id: Iefa13b64084b8e71c881ae08e1ec434d24756c17

In preparation for removing a series of driver methods in
the rationalization of assignment in follow-on patches, we
first create a V9 version of the driver interface. In this
patch, of course, both V8 and V9 are identical.

To create the new V9 driver we:

1) Copied the sql and ldap V8 drivers into their own directory
2) Increased the version of the (new) standard driver to V9
3) Created tests that run the standard sql/ldap Identity tests
against the V8 driver to show, going forward, it is still working.
Since we assume that we never change the sqlalchemy models during
a test run, this turned out to be slight more complex than
anticipated - so created a new tox envlist target for legacy
drivers. Some changes were also needed in the backend assterion
checking for LDAP, to allow for legacy drivers.

commit_message:
Create new version of assignment driver interface

In preparation for removing a series of driver methods in
the rationalization of assignment in follow-on patches, we
first create a V9 version of the driver interface. In this
patch, both V8 and V9 are identical.

To create the new V9 driver we:

1) Copy the sql V8 driver into its own directory to provide a
test for support of a legacy driver
2) Increase the version of the (new) standard driver to V9
3) Create a wrapper for V8 legacy drivers, so that the latest
manager can be driver version-less
4) Create tests that run the standard sql Identity tests
against the V8 driver to show, going forward, it is still working.
Since our existing test strategy assumes that we never change the
sqlalchemy models during a test run, this turned out to be slight
more complex than anticipated - so a new tox envlist target for legacy
drivers is added.

Partially Implements: blueprint assignment-manager-cleanup
Change-Id: Iefa13b64084b8e71c881ae08e1ec434d24756c17

commit_message:
export DATABASES_TO_SAVE for save-state

I noticed this in I45894911c0ee9cd6c9b142d6192350269873d82f where the
"old" database isn't dumped.  This seems to be because "save-state"
calls inc/upgrade:save_mysql_dbs, but it doesn't have access to
DATABASES_TO_SAVE because it's not exported.  An additional trick is
that save-state includes inc/upgrade, so be sure not to overwrite the
variable as blank.

Depends-On: I45894911c0ee9cd6c9b142d6192350269873d82f
Change-Id: I49626dcc277497eaf66d4d998ba8b2655293d28f

[{'created': '2015-12-03 18:08:21.000000000', 'message': 'Remove exposure of routers at package level

Keystone API routers are exposed at their package
level (in __init__.py files). This causes them to
be unnecessarily executed each time something
whithin that package is used.

For example, simply importing
keystone.federation.constants would make the
federation routers code to be executed.

This patch remove routers exposure from package
level and import them directly in services.py,
which is the single place that needs them.

'}]
commit_message:
Remove exposure of routers at package level

Keystone API routers are exposed at their package
level (in __init__.py files). This causes them to
be unnecessarily executed each time something
whithin that package is used.

For example, simply importing
keystone.federation.constants would make the
federation routers code to be executed.

This patch remove routers exposure from package
level and import them directly in services.py,
which is the single place that needs them.

Change-Id: If68184c871ac77659ad2e64aa5f0aafac7a4bf70

commit_message:
Remove invalid TODO related to bug 1265071

There is a TODO note at the SQL catalog backend
saying that not all SQL entities should require
an 'extra' attribute. This is reported as bug
1265071.

This patch removes that note, since the bug has
now been fixed.

Related-Bug: #1265071

Change-Id: Id42e144706e60d599b86dbe17175fe6cd9650604

commit_message:
Revert "Revert "OVS agent reacts to events instead of polling""

The original change had to be reverted because it caused
tests failing in the gate. The failures were due to the
fact that when a port was not ready, an exception was
thrown to trigger a full resync of the agent. This
behavior was meant to be temporary and was fixed in a
dependent patch that was not merged though. This revert
moves the handling of not ready ports in this patch.
It also refactors the unit tests a bit.

This reverts commit e7270d9505fe09ec6d687e7796a814bf883b5416.

Change-Id: I6574cef3c95525ace6a98cf968ee159190681394

commit_message:
Fix stats bug for start_time = 1970-01-01

The api was incorrectly omitting the time
in the where clause if the value was 0, so
check for None instead.

Change-Id: Ic7c225924efce42aae21eb4a909fb877fa6b171f

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2015-11-13 19:56:31.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 28:

My original understanding of this was that we'd store request_spec objects in the API database not the cell one. We don't need it at the cell, only at the top. Sharding the data into the cells is a good goal to keep the api database small, but it introduces complexity of initially putting it in the api db and then moving it to the cell post-schedule.

I would prefer that we start with it in the api db only and never move it. If we want to optimize later once things are working, then we could look at moving it to the cell for the sharding effect. However, given how small the API database is compared to cellsv1, and given that we want to get something that works solidly without failure residue bugs, I think we should do the simpler thing first."}, {'account_id': 5441, 'date': '2015-11-16 22:57:07.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 29.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-11-17 00:28:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 29: Verified-1

[{'created': '2015-08-11 21:32:06.000000000', 'message': 'Add persistence to the RequestSpec object

In order to use the request spec for an instance boot during later
scheduling operations, like resize/migrate, it needs to be persisted.
This adds a db migration to store the request spec and methods to the
object to create/save/get the request spec.

The RequestSpec object is also important for cells v2 so that boot
requests can have their information persisted before the creation of an
instance record in the database.

Change-Id: I94cd50ad29e10eb320d1d78f3081db6519815ff9
Implements: bp persist-request-spec

commit_message:
Add persistence to the RequestSpec object

In order to use the request spec for an instance boot during later
scheduling operations, like resize/migrate, it needs to be persisted.
This adds a db migration to store the request spec and methods to the
object to create/save/get the request spec.

The RequestSpec object is also important for cells v2 so that boot
requests can have their information persisted before the creation of an
instance record in the database.

Change-Id: I94cd50ad29e10eb320d1d78f3081db6519815ff9
Implements: bp persist-request-spec

Yes, the UI is bad, I don't think that's a valid reason to reject this change though.

This only forces the spec writer to touch launchpad twice: once to create the WIP blueprint, and once more to update it once the spec is done. Yes there's a small amount of pain there, but the alternative - which we see right now - is many comments on specs (and changes related to unapproved specs) from people saying "The blueprint is a 404" or "you got the url wrong" or similar.

IMO the user experience in the present situation is far more of a problem than the poor UI on launchpad.'}, {'account_id': 6928, 'date': '2014-07-17 15:37:13.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Patchset 1 was fine. The intuitive thing to do is to create blueprints early for now, especially since all of infra is configured to work with LP in this regard.

Mid-Long term I'd very much like to see us do away with Blueprints (they are super clunky) but given we do still use them for some tracking it seems early to do this today. Perhaps I'm missing something but it seems like the simplest thing to do today is just create them early (like we do in other OpenStack projects)

I've rebased and updated to apply this change to the kilo-template - obviously that can't apply to previous releases.

I agree that this does mean we have to interact a little more with the LP uI, which isn't as pleasant as I'd like. But the present situation has the spec pointing at a URL which 404s, which confuses people reviewing the spec and causes delays getting specs approved.

I agree that the blueprint shouldn't be up until we get consensus on the spec; but as I've suggested that the blueprint should just be a pointer to the spec's review until it lands, I don't think this is a problem. If the spec's author remembers to update the blueprint once the spec lands, that's great; if they don't, at least the BP is already a pointer to the finished spec. Under the current process, there's no BP until the spec lands, so it's easy for the spec author to forget to go back and ever create the BP.

When I first created this change we didn't have a spec for the review process; we now do, so perhaps this change should be documented there instead?"}, {'account_id': 6796, 'date': '2015-03-13 12:08:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review+1

commit_message:
Clarify when the blueprint should be created

Several commenters on Id9addc65f0d2ed519ce4b3edbd561ed660a2786e have
been confused by the fact that the spec includes a reference to a
launchpad blueprint URL that doesn't exist.

This is even more confusing for reviewers of changes like
I9649ee74ebaf62b6b929b28243a07c789a08867c which reference the
blueprint URL as an explanation of why the change is being made - when
the link is broken reviewers have no context that lets them evaluate
the change.

To prevent this being a problem, I've added a note to template.rst
explaining that the blueprint should be created early, and have a
pointer to the change so that reviewers can follow the progress of the
spec.

This change is not itself a spec; it's a change to the process of
creating specs; but I feel as though the same approval process we use
for specs would make sense to use for changing the we suggest creating
specs.

Change-Id: I57bf5e0d73c63120259973515ea26593a2776ba2

commit_message:
Add Rally to networking-ovn

This adds the needed infrastructure to connect networking-ovn
with Rally benchmarking.
A relevant job will be defined to run Neutron with OVN with
the ovn.yaml jobs.
It is easy to defined OVN specific plugins and change the
scenarios run by Rally for OVN using the added files in this
patch.

Change-Id: I7c6a518ba8fb01725cb7a32f5e62062afc16f632

The creation of a volume may fail in such a manner
that a volume in a partial state has been created.
When Openstack comes back re-attempting the creation
operation it fails because the partial volume with
the name already exists.

Solution: When there is a failure creating a volume,
check if a partial volume was created and delete it

commit_message:
NetApp: Cleanup if E-Series volume create fails

The creation of a volume may fail in such a manner
that a volume in a partial state has been created.
When Openstack comes back re-attempting the creation
operation it fails because the partial volume with
the name already exists.

Solution: When there is a failure creating a volume,
check if a partial volume was created and delete it
so any retry will be successful and the storage device
does not contain any dead volumes.

Closes-Bug: 1506940
Change-Id: Id93527a4cab314f27a13d8c08b772fed538d1092
(cherry picked from commit a4bcb1e11bf48207c81e42ba3b9c96f5e13d3ef6)

commit_message:
Use ironic-agent for source-repositories

I recently built a ramdisk for IPA and was confused by
the fact that the source-repositories name did not
match the element name. (this is a convention,
confusing when they don't match but certainly not
required).

This patch makes it so you can use DIB_REPOREF_ironic_agent to
customize the IPA ramdisk sources when building ramdisks.

For backwards compat if DIB_REPOREF_agent is set it automatically
sets the new DIB_REPOREF_ironic_agent to that value as well.

Change-Id: I082d989d0d85601f5984dc7c3767b8d66a3d5438

commit_message:
Fix delete quota of subprojects

This patch aims to fix the bug in which cinder raises
an error when performing a delete quota operation in
a subproject.

Steps to reproduce:
- Create a project A in keystone (e.g openstack project create A);
- Create a project B in keystone with A as its parent (e.g openstack
  project create B --property parent_id=<id of project A>);
- Update the quota value of A (e.g. openstack quota set
  <id of project A> --volume 5)
- Update the quota value of B (e.g. openstack quota set
  <id of project B> --volume 2)
- Try to delete the quota of B (e.g. cinder quota-delete
  <id of project B>)

Change-Id: Id1a749433c3679f1b2adf87ea0a280366c5e4a15
Closes-bug: #1496058
(cherry picked from commit 9a668a0a48135c423a4deda23bb161f6b917ac39)

commit_message:
Update router interface add/delete for ovsdb ovn-nb schema change

The latest ovsdb schema change [1] enables us to use lrouter port
name as router-port option in corresponding lswitch port. This
change is to update the logic accordingly. With this change the
two operations, adding lrouter port and updating peering lswitch
port are combined to a single transaction.

[1] https://github.com/openvswitch/ovs/commit/0000744721bab30bd0db538fb3bc412137d5249f

Closes-bug: 1522540

Change-Id: I6a9f1328e8f6a7cb060dc377e14e3cdf6f014bb9

commit_message:
Refactor OVS-agent tunnel config validate

This change transforms validate_local_ip into a sub-method of
validate_tunnel_config and raises directly SystemExit instead of
indirectly.

Related-bug: #1464394
Change-Id: I35addd41e1a8b061bd0e5e6656a1728fb7fe04ce

commit_message:
Add hv testing for ImageMetaProps._legacy_property_map

Change I03742cc9330814e2758184d8189a5be93a2b978b added the
'hypervisor_type' to the _legacy_property_map. This makes sure that
change is tested.

Also adds test coverage for 'hypervisor_version_requires'.

Related-Bug: #1523503

Change-Id: I3738785a4f119e361be0d6aaf3649ad375c471c8

commit_message:
Replace os.path.join() for URLs

Since os.path.join() is OS-dependent, it should not be used for creating
URLs. This patch replaces the use of os.path.join() in
nova/api/openstack with common.url_join(), which uses the more correct
"/".join(), while preserving the behavior of removing duplicate slashes
inside the URL and adding a trailing slash with an empty final element.
It also adds some tests to ensure that the generate_href() method in
nova/api/openstack/compute/views/versions.py works after the refactoring
to use common.url_join()

Closes-Bug: 1489627
Change-Id: I32948dd1fcf0839b34e446d9e4b08f9c39d17c8f

commit_message:
Fixes TLS processing in the rest driver

The rest driver was not using updated cert utils to
handle processing of TLS certificates and would cause failures.

Also updates build_pem to be py34 compliant.

Change-Id: I05db39ff673083649735434f8e4cc710086ffd54
Closes-Bug: #1507723
(cherry picked from commit I05db39ff673083649735434f8e4cc710086ffd54)

commit_message:
Remove version from setup.cfg

Per [1] we now want to use the git repository for knowing the version
instead of just trying to modify the setup.cfg file.

[1] http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-November/080692.html

Depends-On: Ifa41ef5b856c2726c165a51944069dc1ac3a16cc
Change-Id: I884d1196f0320d85257f521591d36ed7cfbc8013

commit_message:
Update docs for legacy keystone extensions

With most of the legacy extensions were moved to core and
enabled by default, The docs for keystone extension should
be updated accordingly.

Partially implements: bp move-extensions

Change-Id: Iae7eba719992ea941b1267998ee77184eeea7b0f

commit_message:
Checks percent_of_overlap when one boundary is set

Aggregation across metrics have different behavior depending
on if boundary are set and if needed_percent_of_overlap is set.

If boundaries are not set, Carbonara makes the aggregation only with points
at timestamp present in all timeseries.

But when boundaries are set, Carbonara expects that we have certain
percent of timestamps common between timeseries, this percent is controlled
by needed_percent_of_overlap (defaulted with 100%).

This change fixes a weird behavior when only one boundary is set,
the needed_percent_of_overlap wasn't checked.

Change-Id: Ifc85a9004e864d14d42fd482ec144e4d27dd615b
Closes-bug: #1522434

Adds cert_manager option to octavia.conf

Adds the cert manager option the conf file to make it easier
for users to enable Barbican for TLS termination

commit_message:
Remove Neutron FWaaS static example configuration files

Oslo config generator was introduced in patch [1] to
automatically generate the sample Neutron FWaaS configuration
files.

This patch removes the static example configuration files from
the repository as they are now redundant.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/251974/

DocImpact: Update the docs that FWaaS no longer includes static example
configuration files. Instead, use tools/generate_config_file_samples.sh
to generate them and the files generated now end with .sample extension.

Change-Id: I31be3295606ba25929e9af9f40a035ff2b615234
Partially-Implements: blueprint autogen-neutron-conf-file
Partial-bug: #1199963
Depends-On: Ic8208850a27408c8fbeed80ecdb43345aa7dfaa4

commit_message:
Block oslo.messaging 3.1.0 since it breaks Ironic

oslo.messaging change I21d76abf1c30b9e89cb8a6c20d1c0cc79cd83a3f was
released in 3.1.0 and due to debtcollector bug 1520397 it breaks Ironic
loading it's request context serializer.

That was worked around in Ironic on master (mitaka) in commit
37d36f1536944de38a0f7a726e625b893088e1be but that doesn't fix Ironic in
stable/liberty, and we aren't going to backport that workaround to
stable/liberty.

So we need to fix oslo.messaging (either revert the deprecation change
or remove the usage of debtcollector) and release a fix there to fix
stable/liberty, but we still have to block the broken 3.1.0 release.

Related-Bug: #1524041

Change-Id: I3c5a9851ada30b6d7470113014b542b550a4ae8b

base image. We intend to use an image like this to help provision
a docker atomic host for TripleO. It should allow us to
run os-collect-config, various plugins, among other things.

Building this image with DIB is a really handy way to tap
into existing elements for TripleO which already support
the things we need. The downside is that the generated
image is going to be a base image... so there may still
be a case for building a similar image with Dockerfile's

redhat-common within this config file. As such it is Red Hat
specific.

We also exclude the 'base' element to keep things a bit smaller.

commit_message:
Add docker_images_redhat.yaml build-images file

This patch adds a file to help build the heat docker "agent"
base image. We intend to use an image like this to help provision
a docker atomic host for TripleO. It should allow us to
run os-collect-config, various plugins, among other things.

Building this image with DIB is a really handy way to tap
into existing elements for TripleO which already support
the things we need. The downside is that the generated
image is going to be a base image... so there may still
be a case for building a similar image with Dockerfile's
as well. Still... having the the capability to work
with existing elements should significantly speed
up development because we can make use of more robust
elements like source-repositories, etc.

Because of how the docker base element works (and isn't a full
operating system) have had to define elements like yum, and
redhat-common within this config file. As such it is Red Hat
specific.

We also exclude the 'base' element to keep things a bit smaller.

Change-Id: I195c0ef8b844a5fd28a1f4ba465d975787775734

[{'created': '2015-04-15 23:18:34.000000000', 'message': 'Add support for generic controller validations

This patch wires in support for a generic ControllerValidationScript
parameter (currently must be customized via default_parameters in
the Heat environment.) This parameter provides a means to plug
in a custom shell script which can be used to validate
each controller step during the deployment process.

Use of this requires a new heat-config-script element in order
to actually execute the shell script on the node via os-refresh-config.

Change-Id: Ib6f1153f8c2b857c1b2b5c9172a9836da70fe0ce

commit_message:
Add support for generic controller validations

This patch wires in support for a generic controller validations
via a shell script.

Use of this requires a new heat-config-script element in order
to actually execute the shell script on the node via os-refresh-config.

Co-Authored-By: Steven Hardy <shardy@redhat.com>
Change-Id: Ib6f1153f8c2b857c1b2b5c9172a9836da70fe0ce

commit_message:
Stop checking if listener exists when uploading cert

The cert is being uplaoded in the flow BEFORE a listener is being
created. So creating a TLS load balancer will always result in an
error. This removes that check.

Closes-Bug: 1507723

Change-Id: If8d6de33ef7a4e71bdf80115da889da6f0535736
(cherry picked from commit If8d6de33ef7a4e71bdf80115da889da6f0535736)

commit_message:
Add class B3 and an example for C1 to the taxonomy

Be more explicit that OSSA does not cover vulnerabilities in
experimental features, backends and drivers by adding a new class B3
for these in the taxonomy. Also clarify that vulnerabilities relying
on UUID guessing are considered impractical, as an example for class
C1.

Change-Id: Ie73dfb0358913e6bdfeba56e6105f8156382d042

To have the puppet integration jobs part of Health [1] project, we want
logstash about to read subunit-files.
So we need to rename the jobs to match this job filter:
job-filter: '.*(tempest|grenade)-dsvm.*'

That way, we will be able to see the subunit results on [1].
Puppet group already did the necessary to prepare the subunit files, we
just miss this patch to actually rename the jobs.

[1] http://status.openstack.org/openstack-health/#/

Change-Id: Ia41489a913d2adfc00b5f0d9177d1e810e95eec8
"}]
commit_message:
add 'tempest' in puppet-openstack-integration jobs

To have the puppet integration jobs part of Health [1] project, we want
logstash about to read subunit-files.
So we need to rename the jobs to match this job filter:
job-filter: '.*(tempest|grenade)-dsvm.*'

That way, we will be able to see the subunit results on [1].
Puppet group already did the necessary to prepare the subunit files, we
just miss this patch to actually rename the jobs.

[1] http://status.openstack.org/openstack-health/#/

Change-Id: Ia41489a913d2adfc00b5f0d9177d1e810e95eec8

Add better help text to scheduler options

The previous commit moved all the scheduler options to a central
location. This commit adds additional help text to those options.

Blueprint centralize-config-options

- gate-heat-specs-docs http://docs-draft.openstack.org/44/135444/8/gate/gate-heat-specs-docs/e4764e4//doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 2m 37s
- gate-heat-specs-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/44/135444/8/gate/gate-heat-specs-python27/3feebd1/ : SUCCESS in 2m 01s'}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2015-12-03 17:57:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

Is it too late for me to throw a spanner in the works?

I think that putting this stuff in the template is a mistake. I don't see update restrictions as a way of declaring stuff that will never change (how could you possibly know this in advance when, as a former colleague once memorably put it, "it's not the future yet"?). Rather, it should be a way of putting either a user or a validation tool into the loop:

stack update-preview -> approve changes -> stack update

In the most common use case, you'd just be passing the output of update-preview directly into update, to restrict Heat to making only the changes you approved. IMHO this argues strongly for this data to be passed in alongside the template, not edited into it.

Also, putting restrictions like this into the template breaks the declarative model. Say you have a Git history of your deployment... you should be able to move from any point in that history to any other point with a single stack update. If there are times when that would be a bad idea and you want a tool to stop you from even trying in those situations, that's great. But if you have to step through every intermediate revision in order to be able to guarantee a transformation from one revision to another, then what you have is no longer a declarative system in any meaningful sense.

To give a concrete example:

Template A: You create some resources
Template B: You realise that some of them need to change
Template C: You decide that those ones are now fixed for all time, so you disallow further updates of them

A user who has deployed template version A can no longer update to the latest version, C, without first updating to B.

i.e. we're mixing declarations that are absolute with stuff that is relative to the last revision.'}, {'account_id': 13720, 'date': '2015-12-07 15:14:25.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

(1 comment)

Great catch, Zane. We have a nice property with the template language that stack deployment does NOT depend on the history of the stack, and adding this kind of resource restrictions would break the nice declarative model.


I'm not sure how we can accurately predict the behavior of a resource without such a restriction though. One of the really important (and frequent) questions we face from customers is to know whether updating a stack will blow away their existing resources. In that situation, having something in the template that explicitly restricts this is a godsend."}, {'account_id': 18029, 'date': '2015-12-07 17:19:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

There is also a scenario where the operator and/or 3rd party may provide templates for end users to use. In that case, the author may not want end user to update a resource since they may not have knowledge about what/how that resource works. Adding a mechanism for a author to mark the resource as not safe for update, would allow design where an intermediary api can provide that information to end user.'}, {'account_id': 7253, 'date': '2015-12-07 20:32:17.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

(1 comment)

This use case is what stack update preview is for.  What if there is a window of time where an update replace is acceptable?  Would the user need to first remove the restrictions, then do the update, then add the restrictions back again?  The stack-update preview workflow that Zane proposed would be much less work from the users' POV."}, {'account_id': 7253, 'date': '2015-12-07 20:46:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

Here is a related blueprint https://review.openstack.org/#/c/241755/'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2015-12-07 21:30:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

I've been looking at stack update preview recently, and although I can see it as useful in this context (particularly when I've fixed bug #1521971), I personally don't see it as a complete replacement for what was proposed here.

E.g, we're relying on an external approval workflow, which not the same thing as providing a template annotation which says "do not ever replace"

There are times when you want the latter, e.g you do not ever want all servers in your stack to be rebuilt because you inadvertently change the user_data property, and I can see users preferring a "do not replace" argument (either in the template or potentially environment) because it *is* more declarative than saying "implement an external workflow".

So I'm not sure I really buy the non-declarative argument tbh - how is having an annotation to define mutability and const-ness breaking the declarative model?

One observation is that this functionality already exists in another well known cloud orchestration service, and it's implemented via a policy declared separately from the template.  Would a compromise be to enable per-resource annotation of update policy in the resource registry? (I'm thinking similar to hooks here).'}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2015-12-09 20:56:51.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

I agree that there might be two different use cases here - one is to enforce the results of your update-preview so you can guarantee that even if e.g. somebody else updates the stack in between you doing update-preview and update, you get to enforce what update-preview predicted; and the second is to permanently mark some resources as not ones you ever want to replace.

The latter *could* go in the template, but IMHO only if the restriction was applied only when it appeared *both* before and after the update. That's inconsistent with how current update policies are applied and will almost certainly lead to confusion. I can picture the bug reports already.

I do prefer the idea of putting it in the environment to having it in the template, but I don't think that solves the issue.

Making it an API think where you explicitly lock a resource would solve the issue, but I suspect people will have valid reasons to dislike that as a solution.

I think the answer is probably that we need to have an integrated approach between the fixed and transient restrictions. So the transient ones would override the fixed ones, but the fixed ones would be taken into account when producing the update-preview output, in such that it would always be safe to pipe the output of update-preview into the update API and not have it start replacing resources with fixed restrictions."}]

commit_message:
Let users restrict stack-update scope

A spec describing a new option for stack update that will let users
protect certain resources from being destroyed/replaced in that update.

Change-Id: Ib29abad41d03e7054debd346ad9ee333421b6b21
BP: stack-update-restrict

commit_message:
test requirements with grenade multinode

We only have a single voting multinode job, which is the grenade
partial upgrade job. Things like backportability of objects, and
actually going across a network get tested here in ways that no other
job tests. We should also use this test for requirements.

Change-Id: I9e6ff2e79ab1a59b7d1e4661b2f2030d8e453581

commit_message:
Adding oneview.common tests for some method not well tested

This is the first of a patch series to improve OneView driver unit
testing. There are some functions at oneview.common that need more
test cases. This change add test cases to cover specific scenarios
for 'get_oneview_info' and '_verify_node_info' functions.

Change-Id: Id1246bc5366018d642874bfbde23b6b13763f322

commit_message:
devstack: Switch back to ovs master.

The conntrack kernel backport has been merged back into ovs master, so
we can drop the use of a custom branch.

Change-Id: I049525257cf615b60965bdb655e884c4b7316e0d
Signed-off-by: Russell Bryant <rbryant@redhat.com>

commit_message:
devstack: Update list of kernel modules to load.

Update the list of kernel modules to explicitly load before openvswitch
to resolve some errors I've seen on different failures.  Related, if
openvswitch still fails to load, get dmesg output.

Change-Id: Iadcb1feed89fb53333724edc0df71335eda81a3f
Signed-off-by: Russell Bryant <rbryant@redhat.com>

EMC VNX: Add share extend support

This commit is to add share extend support in EMC VNX driver.
In addition, it includes the fix of minor nit from
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/252267/

Change-Id: I23b98d7a106803edbbf68e0dcbdaddf38163d4d1
Implements: blueprint emc-vnx-driver-extend-share

commit_message:
Adding devref about genconfig

This adds a description of the generation of opts.py and
cinder.conf.sample, the commands to generate them, and the scripts
that do the work generating them.

Change-Id: I6217e81acb9ee49c66cd510d55b40e1fd6fc3b3b

commit_message:
iPXE: use set arithmetic to increment the value of a variable

The "inc" command doesn't exist on really old iPXE ROMs so we need to
create a basic arithmetic mechanism using set to do it.

Note: I find this patch really ugly, I would prefer people to just
update their iPXE ROM instead. But I'm putting it up and leaving for
comments anyway.

Change-Id: Idcf13d8a6124a5b0b26a7c3b959d3749f2383933
Closes-Bug: #1507738

commit_message:
Explicitly use asyncio protocol for websockets

The new default for txaio (dependency of autobahn) requires that you
specify how you want websocket connections to be managed (asyncio or
twisted) and raises an exception if you don't make a choice.

Change-Id: I40695b17916cdd1795778be654a427210192ee2f

commit_message:
Implementing DevStack support for networking-sfc

This patch implements devstack plugin changes for deploying
networking-sfc solution via devStack.

Note: Download all sfc code and do
./unstack.sh and ./stack.sh

Change-Id: Id9453685c81a7bfdf7e72ce9f0dba0e307333037
Co-Authored-By: vikram.choudhary <vikram.choudhary@huawei.com>

commit_message:
Included namespace_prefix logic in toscaparser

if namespace_prefix is provided in imports, the full name will be
namespace_prefix.type while importing type definition from namespace.

Partially Implements: blueprint tosca-namespaces

Change-Id: I8fb43a6db2fc040713f41c75a80e27abbe451ea1

commit_message:
Address potential races in SolidFire VAG

While building the initial volume access group solution I realized there were
race conditions present. This patch attempts to address those by being far
more careful during VAG creation and removal. Tracking multiattach volume
detaches around VAG volume removal introduced all sorts of future race
conditions so instead multiattach volumes are treated differently and are only
removed from VAGs on volume removal. Not ideal but it'll get the job done.

Think I covered all the new branches with unit tests. Complexity was introduced
but it should be worth it due to the safety that was also introduced.

Change-Id: I80034cdf759295c8d379c02ed9e42659590b41a9

[{'created': '2015-12-04 14:51:34.000000000', 'message': 'fix pecan _lookup usage

_lookup routing in pecan is expected to be an object method. we
incorrectly set it to static which throws a few warnings. this patch
fixes it.

Closes-Bug: #1521283
Change-Id: I0911cbe830eef84af613e08dc9495109d27a1646
(cherry picked from commit 96e43af961a3d1722425e6f03822f4a217c68c08)
'}]
commit_message:
fix pecan _lookup usage

_lookup routing in pecan is expected to be an object method. we
incorrectly set it to static which throws a few warnings. this patch
fixes it.

Closes-Bug: #1521283
Change-Id: I0911cbe830eef84af613e08dc9495109d27a1646
(cherry picked from commit 96e43af961a3d1722425e6f03822f4a217c68c08)

[{'created': '2015-12-04 14:51:14.000000000', 'message': "fix expunge_metrics method

expunge_metrics method does not work properly. it uses list_metrics
from indexer to get metrics with status == 'delete'. this makes sense
but list_metrics itself is hardcoded to always search for 'active'
status. because of that, the query will always be look for status ==
'active' and status == 'delete' which can't happen so it never finds
any match.

Change-Id: I318fa5b4642a187776dce23ee9a933a5f852c4f8
(cherry picked from commit f6a61a289dfe20bd8cf1ce597ac415323ddf8c1a)
"}]
commit_message:
fix expunge_metrics method

expunge_metrics method does not work properly. it uses list_metrics
from indexer to get metrics with status == 'delete'. this makes sense
but list_metrics itself is hardcoded to always search for 'active'
status. because of that, the query will always be look for status ==
'active' and status == 'delete' which can't happen so it never finds
any match.

Change-Id: I318fa5b4642a187776dce23ee9a933a5f852c4f8
(cherry picked from commit f6a61a289dfe20bd8cf1ce597ac415323ddf8c1a)

commit_message:
tests: improve fake Swift client delete_container

You cannot delete a container that is not empty.

Change-Id: I056212df060ff20325fbc55c8ad5fa6add6d9f40
(cherry picked from commit 2ff4b5136a15952f0303d20e883ca34ebb418baf)

ALTER TYPE ... ADD cannot run inside a transaction block,
therefore we use another way to update it.

Change-Id: I8c6f62b7642917a2ea1bc0280e41261797aca172

commit_message:
fix error in alembic when upgrade postgresql

ALTER TYPE ... ADD cannot run inside a transaction block,
therefore we use another way to update it.

Change-Id: I8c6f62b7642917a2ea1bc0280e41261797aca172
Closes-Bug: #1520777
(cherry picked from commit 20418cd339af775842e84c2b6d2a820289888f00)

commit_message:
Update Liberty SHA's - 9 Dec 2015

Updates all repo SHAs to open up work on 12.0.3

This also includes a move of the Aodh repository to
playbooks/defaults/repo_packages/openstack_services.yml
as it now has a stable/liberty branch, and an update
of the policy.json template based on the one available
in the stable branch.

Change-Id: If0114d8f04cff8203f3ac36c71b8d19f9909708c

uuidstnl.inst2
uuidstnl.inst3

Then it would be a little easier to keep track of the 1 2 3 in the code strings, and make the lines a little shorter.

commit_message:
Implements proper UUID format for the ComputeAPITestCase

Currently unittests are using non valid UUID format for the
FieldType UUID. This is used across many objects.

This is preparation work to add UUID validation in the
oslo_versionedobjects/fields.py.

Without this change adding validation will cause tests to fail.

Change-Id: Iaad96b4185d19055dff40450eab2a1818b7054a0

commit_message:
Change endpoint.url column type to String

Change endpoint.url column type from TEXT to VARCHAR, to be able to
include the url field in a unique constraint that avoids the creation of
duplicated endpoints.

Co-Authored-By: Raildo Mascena <raildo@lsd.ufcg.edu.br>

Change-Id: I4d9fdf53dd3f6be7e9b288fd95a12bc0b4dd81fc
Partial-Bug: 1376937

commit_message:
Fix Create Endpoint API Status Code

The v3 API returns 200 OK on endpoint creation. This patch fixes our
documentation to make it consistent.

Closes-Bug: #1522577

Change-Id: I66c053f633b7e7ac38715e9d62c3cb2ecad2cc43

commit_message:
Numerous debug messages due to iso8601 log level

iso8601 is indirectly used by keystone client and removing
the log level iso8601=WARNING results in numerous debug messages.
This patch reverts iso8601=WARNING log level removal introduced
in 37816a0e63ed48ed3763e8c312fbb42c14b92167 commit.

Change-Id: I9367cc0f39e6f08b0cf437c02100c74c9bc126d2

commit_message:
tests: block when acquiring processing lock

In tests, not blocking when processing the data in background might
trigger a race condition since all the tests run in parallel on the same
database.

commit_message:
Simplify RDO install

We can just directly install the latest RDO repo rather than having to
keep this up-to-date.  I don't think there is actually much there we
need any more; there was a lot more coming from RDO in the centos6
days.  openvswitch is one big one, however.

(cherry picked from commit 1eca508c57dd987fa6f7a7e6f441096365e6892d)

Change-Id: Ibce834c3e76d71a770013cf1b469aa86396751b9

commit_message:
Remove httpretty from requirements

We've had problems with this with packaging and pinning requirements.
requests-mock is a already accepted and used replacement so remove
httpretty in favour of that.

Change-Id: I2382c6a0425c98bf969127b2e11f9d6926e52c53

commit_message:
Skip keystone endpoint test due to bug 1522577

That bug reports that endpoint creation should
return HTTP 201 Created status code.

There is a tempest test checking the status
code is 200 OK. Such test is now skipped and
will be restored once keystone change [1] lands.

[1] Ic17a8cb0181bb864094b28edfee61e1e65c1ca93

Related-Bug: #1522577

Change-Id: I872d362f92b51ff785e8dd7602a8734a0762c96f

commit_message:
Python 3: fix a lot of tests

As of this commit, the following tests should now be working with Python 3:

- cinder.tests.unit.api.contrib.test_cgsnapshots
- cinder.tests.unit.api.contrib.test_scheduler_hints
- cinder.tests.unit.api.contrib.test_snapshot_actions
- cinder.tests.unit.api.contrib.test_snapshot_manage
- cinder.tests.unit.api.contrib.test_snapshot_unmanage
- cinder.tests.unit.api.contrib.test_volume_encryption_metadata
- cinder.tests.unit.api.contrib.test_volume_host_attribute
- cinder.tests.unit.api.contrib.test_volume_manage
- cinder.tests.unit.api.contrib.test_volume_migration_status_attribute
- cinder.tests.unit.api.contrib.test_volume_tenant_attribute
- cinder.tests.unit.api.contrib.test_volume_unmanage
- cinder.tests.unit.api.v2.test_volumes

Most changes in this patch:
- make sure that Request.body is set to bytes;
- replace jsonutils.dumps with jsonutils.dump_as_bytes;
- replace json.loads with oslo_serialization.jsonutils.loads;
- replace dict.iteritems with dict.items.

Partial-Implements: blueprint cinder-python3
Change-Id: Icbb96ff84b7012b58f7296eea4fbcd620e081614

commit_message:
Fix endpoint test related to bug 1522577

That bug reports that endpoint creation should
return HTTP 201 Created status code.

There was a tempest test checking the status
code which was skipped in the parent change [1].

This patch restores and fixes the check of status
code for endpoint creation.

[1] I872d362f92b51ff785e8dd7602a8734a0762c96f

Depends-On: Ic17a8cb0181bb864094b28edfee61e1e65c1ca93
Change-Id: I9fc4b224324e900a4bbe1b390ecb96bee2f6290c

neutron is executed by 'python' in lib/neutron-legacy. for example it is the following.

run_process q-svc "python ..."

so we should add something like the following.

lib/neutron-legacy:
function start_neutron_service_and_check {
...
    local python_cmd
    local python_versions=$(get_python_versions_for_package neutron)
    if [[ $PYTHON3_VERSION =~ $python_versions ]]; then
        python_cmd=python${PYTHON3_VERSION}
    else
        python_cmd=python
    fi
...
    run_process q-svc "$python_cmd ..."
    run_process q-agt "$python_cmd ..."
...'}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2015-07-15 14:26:28.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

'}, {'created': '2015-09-26 12:38:05.000000000', 'message': 'Enable optional Python 3 support

python 3 if they indicate support in their python package metadata.

- test-requirements of a certain project is additionally installed so
  as to allow projects to install any python 3 test dependencies they
  might be missing otherwise.

  that accounts for hash randomization.

commit_message:
Enable optional Python 3 support

Add USE_PYTHON3 and PYTHON3_VERSION variables to allow services to use
python 3 if they indicate support in their python package metadata.

Tested in Heat here -> I837c2fba682ab430d50e9f43913f2fed20325a7a.
Project config change to add a dedicated job to Heat is here -> I0837e62d6ccc66397a5e409f0961edd4be31f467

Change-Id: I079e18b58b214bf8362945c253d6d894ca8b1a6b
